  "prompt": "When should I prune my roses?",
  "response": "The best time to prune roses depends on the type of rose and your local climate:\n\n1. Hybrid Tea, Floribunda, and Grandiflora Roses:\n- Prune in late winter or early spring, just before new growth begins\n- Usually around February or March, when the risk of hard frost has passed\n\n2. Climbing Roses:\n- Prune after flowering, typically in late summer or early fall\n- Remove dead or weak canes and shape the plant\n\n3. Shrub and Old Garden Roses:\n- Prune lightly after flowering\n- Major pruning in late winter or early spring\n\n4. Once-Blooming Roses:\n- Prune immediately after flowering, usually in early summer\n\nGeneral pruning tips:\n- Use clean, sharp pruning shears\n- Cut at a 45-degree angle just above an outward-facing bud\n- Remove dead, diseased, or crossing branches\n- Cut out thin or weak canes\n\nThe exact timing can vary depending on your specific climate and rose variety, so it's best to consult local gardening resources or a nursery for precise guidance.",
